issue.title: Migrate test_bson.py to pytest (POC)
issue.body:
Migrate test_bson.py to pytest (POC)

Summary
This PR refactors test/test_bson.py from unittest.TestCase style to idiomatic pytest. It keeps behavior identical, while establishing a low-churn pattern for migrating the rest of the suite.

Key changes
- Drop unittest.TestCase inheritance in TestBSON, TestCodecOptions, TestDatetimeConversion, and TestLongLongToString
- Introduce a lightweight _PyAssertMixin that provides common unittest-style helpers implemented via pytest:
  - assertEqual/assertTrue/etc. map to native assert
  - assertRaises/assertRaisesRegex implemented with pytest.raises, supporting both call and context-manager styles and exposing .exception for compatibility
  - assertWarns via pytest.warns
  - fail and assertNotIsInstance
- Replace @unittest.skip with @pytest.mark.skip(reason=...)
- No semantic changes to tests

Verification
- Tight loop: python -m pytest -q test/test_bson.py
- Result: 86 passed, 1 deselected locally
- CI: See checks below once they run

Repeatable migration pattern
- Replace TestCase inheritance with a simple mixin (or use direct asserts progressively)
- Convert:
  - self.assertX -> assert ...
  - self.assertRaises(E, fn, ...) -> with pytest.raises(E): fn(...)
  - with self.assertRaises(E) as ctx: ... -> with pytest.raises(E) as ctx: ...; str(ctx.value) instead of ctx.exception if preferred
  - self.assertRaisesRegex(E, "re") -> pytest.raises(E, match="re")
  - self.assertWarns(W) -> pytest.warns(W)
  - @unittest.skip("reason") -> @pytest.mark.skip(reason="reason")
- Prefer idiomatic pytest going forward:
  - Assert with bare assert
  - Use pytest.raises/.warns context managers directly
  - Leverage pytest fixtures from test/conftest.py (setup/teardown already wired)
  - Consider parametrization where it meaningfully reduces duplication

Notes
- The _PyAssertMixin is intended as a transitional helper to minimize diff and risk. As further tests are migrated, we can incrementally remove mixin methods and adopt native pytest idioms.
- Scope is limited to test/test_bson.py only.

Links
- Link to Devin run: https://app.devin.ai/sessions/0845077b699f401cadf4b4c9bfb81d82
- Requested by: Prashant Mital (@prashantmital)

pull_request.title: Add demo: Cantilevered beam (DOLFINx) ‚Äî linear elasticity with end-face traction
pull_request.body:
# Refactor cantilever demo into instructional functional modules for numerical methods learning ## Summary This PR refactors the cantilever beam demonstration script to better highlight key numerical methods concepts for beginners. The original linear script has been reorganized into clear functional modules that map directly to the fundamental stages of finite element analysis: - **Geometry**: `make_geometry()` - defines beam dimensions in 3D space - **Discretization**: `discretize()` - creates hexahedral mesh and vector function space - **Boundary Conditions**: `apply_boundary_conditions()` - enforces clamped constraints - **Matrix Construction**: `build_forms()` + `assemble_system()` - separates form definition from assembly - **Linear Solver**: `solve_system()` - explicit PETSc KSP configuration and solving - **Analysis & Results**: `analyze_and_export()` - strain/stress computation and visualization output **Key Technical Change**: Replaced `LinearProblem` with explicit matrix assembly (`fem_petsc.assemble_matrix`/`assemble_vector`) and PETSc KSP solver to clearly separate "matrix construction" from "linear solver" stages as requested for educational purposes. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **End-to-end execution test**: Run `python python/demo/demo_cantilever_beam.py` from repo root and verify it completes without errors - [ ] **Numerical correctness**: Check that displacement norm and solution patterns are reasonable for a cantilever beam - [ ] **Educational clarity**: Verify the functional decomposition makes the numerical methods pipeline clear and easy to follow - [ ] **Solver verification**: Confirm the PETSc KSP configuration (`preonly`/`lu`) works correctly and converges - [ ] **Visualization outputs**: Open generated XDMF files in ParaView to verify beam deflection and stress patterns look physically correct **Recommended test plan**: Execute the demo, then load `out_cantilever/*.xdmf` in ParaView to visually inspect that the cantilever shows expected deflection (max at free end) and stress distribution (tension/compression on opposite faces). --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD DemoFile["python/demo/
demo_cantilever_beam.py"]:::major-edit DolfinxFem["dolfinx.fem

(TrialFunction, TestFunction)"]:::context PETSc["petsc4py.PETSc
(KSP solver)"]:::context XDMFOutput["out_cantilever/
*.xdmf files"]:::major-edit DemoFile --> DolfinxFem DemoFile --> FemPetsc DemoFile --> DolfinxMesh DemoFile --> UFL DemoFile --> PETSc DemoFile --> XDMFOutput DemoFile -.->|"replaced LinearProblem
with explicit assembly"| FemPetsc DemoFile -.->|"explicit KSP solver
configuration"| PETSc subgraph Legend L1[Major Edit]:::major-edit L2[Minor Edit]:::minor-edit L3[Context/No Edit]:::context end classDef major-edit fill:#90EE90 classDef minor-edit fill:#87CEEB classDef context fill:#FFFFFF ``` ### Notes - **Risk**: This is a substantial refactor with no local testing performed - there's significant potential for runtime errors or incorrect results - **Educational Impact**: The functional structure now clearly maps to the 6 requested numerical methods concepts, making it much more instructional for beginners - **API Change**: Moving from `LinearProblem` to explicit assembly/KSP is a major change that exposes the matrix construction and solver stages separately - **Missing Documentation**: Some docstrings were accidentally removed during cleanup - the educational value could be enhanced by adding them back - **Link to Devin run**: https://app.devin.ai/sessions/f443cb377a30474a8f57791f75d8d205 - **Requested by**: prashantmital (@prashantmital)

pull_request.title: chore: Add Claude Code GitHub Workflow
pull_request.body:
## ü§ñ Installing Claude Code GitHub App

This PR adds a GitHub Actions workflow that enables Claude Code integration in our repository.

### What is Claude Code?

[Claude Code](https://claude.ai/code) is an AI coding agent that can help with:
- Bug fixes and improvements  
- Documentation updates
- Implementing new features
- Code reviews and suggestions
- Writing tests
- And more!

### How it works

Once this PR is merged, we'll be able to interact with Claude by mentioning @claude in a pull request or issue comment.
Once the workflow is triggered, Claude will analyze the comment and surrounding context, and execute on the request in a GitHub action.

### Important Notes

- **This workflow won't take effect until this PR is merged**
- **@claude mentions won't work until after the merge is complete**
- The workflow runs automatically whenever Claude is mentioned in PR or issue comments
- Claude gets access to the entire PR or issue context including files, diffs, and previous comments

### Security

- Our Anthropic API key is securely stored as a GitHub Actions secret
- Only users with write access to the repository can trigger the workflow
- All Claude runs are stored in the GitHub Actions run history
- Claude's default tools are limited to reading/writing files and interacting with our repo by creating comments, branches, and commits.
- We can add more allowed tools by adding them to the workflow file like:

```
allowed_tools: Bash(npm install),Bash(npm run build),Bash(npm run lint),Bash(npm run test)
```

There's more information in the [Claude Code action repo](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code-action).

After merging this PR, let's try mentioning @claude in a comment on any PR to get started!

commits.message:
Add --defs-yaml-template flag to DG CLI inspect-component command

## Summary & Motivation

Adds a new `--defs-yaml-template` flag to the `dg utils inspect-component` command that generates comprehensive YAML templates for component definition files. This feature helps developers understand component structure by providing both schema documentation and example values in a single output.

The template generator creates structured YAML with:
- Schema documentation section with field types, requirements, and descriptions
- Example values section with valid YAML using realistic sample data
- Support for complex nested objects, arrays, and schema references
- Automatic handling of optional vs required fields

Example usage:
```bash
dg utils inspect-component dagster_dbt.DbtProjectComponent --defs-yaml-template
```

This complements the existing `--component-schema` flag by providing a more user-friendly format that developers can directly copy and modify for their component configurations.

## How I Tested These Changes

Added comprehensive unit tests covering the new flag functionality, template generation for various component types, and validation that prevents multiple flags from being used simultaneously. Existing test suite continues to pass.

## Changelog

[DG CLI] Added `--defs-yaml-template` flag to `dg utils inspect-component` command to generate comprehensive YAML templates for component definition files.

issue.title: Add demo: Cantilevered beam (DOLFINx) ‚Äî linear elasticity with end-face traction
issue.body:
# Refactor cantilever demo into instructional functional modules for numerical methods learning ## Summary This PR refactors the cantilever beam demonstration script to better highlight key numerical methods concepts for beginners. The original linear script has been reorganized into clear functional modules that map directly to the fundamental stages of finite element analysis: - **Geometry**: `make_geometry()` - defines beam dimensions in 3D space - **Discretization**: `discretize()` - creates hexahedral mesh and vector function space - **Boundary Conditions**: `apply_boundary_conditions()` - enforces clamped constraints - **Matrix Construction**: `build_forms()` + `assemble_system()` - separates form definition from assembly - **Linear Solver**: `solve_system()` - explicit PETSc KSP configuration and solving - **Analysis & Results**: `analyze_and_export()` - strain/stress computation and visualization output **Key Technical Change**: Replaced `LinearProblem` with explicit matrix assembly (`fem_petsc.assemble_matrix`/`assemble_vector`) and PETSc KSP solver to clearly separate "matrix construction" from "linear solver" stages as requested for educational purposes. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **End-to-end execution test**: Run `python python/demo/demo_cantilever_beam.py` from repo root and verify it completes without errors - [ ] **Numerical correctness**: Check that displacement norm and solution patterns are reasonable for a cantilever beam - [ ] **Educational clarity**: Verify the functional decomposition makes the numerical methods pipeline clear and easy to follow - [ ] **Solver verification**: Confirm the PETSc KSP configuration (`preonly`/`lu`) works correctly and converges - [ ] **Visualization outputs**: Open generated XDMF files in ParaView to verify beam deflection and stress patterns look physically correct **Recommended test plan**: Execute the demo, then load `out_cantilever/*.xdmf` in ParaView to visually inspect that the cantilever shows expected deflection (max at free end) and stress distribution (tension/compression on opposite faces). --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD DemoFile["python/demo/
demo_cantilever_beam.py"]:::major-edit DolfinxFem["dolfinx.fem
(Function, Expression, etc.)"]:::context FemPetsc["dolfinx.fem.petsc
(assemble_matrix, assemble_vector)"]:::context DolfinxMesh["dolfinx.mesh
(create_box)"]:::context UFL["ufl
(TrialFunction, TestFunction)"]:::context PETSc["petsc4py.PETSc
(KSP solver)"]:::context XDMFOutput["out_cantilever/
*.xdmf files"]:::major-edit DemoFile --> DolfinxFem DemoFile --> FemPetsc DemoFile --> DolfinxMesh DemoFile --> UFL DemoFile --> PETSc DemoFile --> XDMFOutput DemoFile -.->|"replaced LinearProblem
with explicit assembly"| FemPetsc DemoFile -.->|"explicit KSP solver
configuration"| PETSc subgraph Legend L1[Major Edit]:::major-edit L2[Minor Edit]:::minor-edit L3[Context/No Edit]:::context end classDef major-edit fill:#90EE90 classDef minor-edit fill:#87CEEB classDef context fill:#FFFFFF ``` ### Notes - **Risk**: This is a substantial refactor with no local testing performed - there's significant potential for runtime errors or incorrect results - **Educational Impact**: The functional structure now clearly maps to the 6 requested numerical methods concepts, making it much more instructional for beginners - **API Change**: Moving from `LinearProblem` to explicit assembly/KSP is a major change that exposes the matrix construction and solver stages separately - **Missing Documentation**: Some docstrings were accidentally removed during cleanup - the educational value could be enhanced by adding them back - **Link to Devin run**: https://app.devin.ai/sessions/f443cb377a30474a8f57791f75d8d205 - **Requested by**: prashantmital (@prashantmital)

issue.title: AndroidX considering dropping support for .pom files
issue.body:
AndroidX is considering dropping support for `.pom` files and just using `.module`. `.pom` files do not really work with KMP, where there is no such thing as a single artifact, it all depends on the consumer, e.g. if the consumer if JVM vs Android you get a different artifact. AndroidX KMP usage is growing, and we keep putting in really ugly workarounds in our build to keep .pom files barely usable (e.g. https://github.com/bazel-contrib/rules_jvm_external/issues/864). The maintenance burden has really reached a tipping point.

This change would be a no-op for our Gradle users, but likely breaking for alternative build system users (e.g Bazel, Buck, etc).

I can see that Bazel is looking to support Gradle resolver (https://github.com/bazel-contrib/rules_jvm_external/pull/1357)
instead of using poms. This change would be required for all the bazel users to keep consuming AndroidX artifacts.

We would obviously give an x month heads up to the world when we do this change.

I wanted to create this issue to start the discussion.
